  "prompt": "When the hydronium-ion concentration of a solution is 1\u00d710\u221212 M , what is the pH of the solution?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of a solution given the hydronium-ion concentration, you can use the formula:\n\n\\[ \\text{pH} = -\\log[\\text{H}_3\\text{O}^+] \\]\n\nGiven that the hydronium-ion concentration \\([\\text{H}_3\\text{O}^+]\\) is \\(1 \\times 10^{-12} \\, \\text{M}\\), you can plug this value into the formula:\n\n\\[ \\text{pH} = -\\log(1 \\times 10^{-12}) \\]\n\nNow, calculate the logarithm:\n\n\\[ \\log(1 \\times 10^{-12}) = -12 \\]\n\nSo,\n\n\\[ \\text{pH} = -(-12) = 12 \\]\n\nTherefore, the pH of the solution is **12**.",
